article.description: Antoine Walker scored 22 points and rookie J.R. Bremer added 20 as the Celtics defeated the Toronto Raptors 90-85 on Friday night, despite playing without Pierce for the first time in more than three years.
article.headline: Pierce's streak of 257 straight games played ends

images.name: Bremer JR 030228 inline
images.caption: Celtics rookie J.R. Bremer fought off the Raptors for 20 points, six rebounds and five assists.

article.linkText: Without Pierce, Celtics find a way to ice Raptors
article.story:
BOSTON (AP) -- Even without Paul Pierce, the Boston Celtics found a way to win. Antoine Walker scored 22 points and rookie J.R. Bremer added 20 as the Celtics defeated the Toronto Raptors 90-85 on Friday night, despite playing without Pierce for the first time in more than three years. Walker sealed the game when he hit a 17-foot fadeaway from the left side with 18.8 seconds left. "This is a meaningful win, especially because of the situation,'' Walker said. "We're fighting for home-court advantage and we were able to get a big win tonight without Paul.'' The Celtics, who were 1-10 without Pierce in the lineup entering the game, won their second straight game while Toronto has lost three of four after a four-game winning streak. The Raptors fell to 6-21 on the road. Vince Carter, who sprained his neck in a collision with Walker in the fourth quarter and is day-to-day, led the Raptors with 18 points while Antonio Davis added 13 points and 14 rebounds. Pierce, who had played in 257 consecutive games, the third-longest streak among active players, sat out because of a lower back he strained while slipping on ice last Saturday. The last game Pierce missed was on Jan. 26, 2000 at Orlando because of a hamstring pull. Tony Delk hit a 3-pointer with 5:52 left in the fourth quarter to give Boston its biggest lead at 83-71 before the Raptors went on an 8-0 run capped by a jump hook by Davis. Walker hit a layup that pushed the lead to 85-69, but Voshon Lenard's 3-pointer cut the deficit to three. A layup by Eric Williams made it 87-82, but Alvin Williams made a 3-pointer that made it a two-point game. "They did a nice job of pounding the ball down low to Eric Williams,'' Raptors forward Jerome Williams said. "Bremer really stepped up and was able to knock down the open 3 and put pressure on us from the outside.'' Walker was just 9-of-28 from the field and missed all four of his 3-point attempts, but he grabbed 11 rebounds and had nine assists. Bremer, coming off an 0-for-7 performance in a 71-69 win over Indiana on Wednesday, also finished with six rebounds and five assists. "Today I was knocking down open shots,'' Bremer said. "Last game I wasn't able to hit them. It was a really good time for me to step it up with our leading scorer out. I'm glad it came on a night like tonight.'' Walker was 3-of-15 in the first half and Boston made just 2-of-12 of its 3-point attempts, but the Celtics still managed to take a 44-41 lead into the break. "We have more weapons than we did a couple of years ago when Paul missed some games,'' Celtics coach Jim O'Brien said. "Anytime you can get a win like that without one of your All-Stars, it's very important.'' Eric Williams added 18 for Boston.

Game notes
Morris Peterson is the only player for the Raptors to play in all 55 games this season. ... New England Patriots quarterback Tom Brady was in attendance, wearing a San Francisco Giants cap. ... Raptors forward Michael Bradley grew up in nearby Worcester, Mass. ... Celtics center Vin Baker served the first game of an indefinite suspension. ... Kedrick Brown replaced Pierce in the starting lineup and finished with two points.
